 This confirms not only that at least some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory already widely accepted, but provides details that fossils generally cannot provide, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
 Scientists say the animal's plumage was brownish-brown on top and pale or carotenoid on the underside.
 This discovery also helps to better understand the evolution of feathers in birds.
 Since dinosaur feathers did not have a fully developed stem, called a rachis, but still showed other features typical of feathers – barbs and barbules – the researchers concluded that the rachis was probably an evolutionary development later than these other features.
 The structure of the feathers suggests that they were not used for flight but rather for regulation or temperature display. The researchers suggested that, even though it is the tail of a juvenile dinosaur, the specimen shows adult plumage and not downy feathers of a chick.
 The scientists say that this is indeed the tail of a juvenile dinosaur, but the sample reveals a plumage belonging to an adult, not a young.
