 In France, voting is traditionally a low-tech experience: voters seal themselves in a booth, put a pre-printed paper ballot in an envelope, and drop it in a box.
 After the officers verify his identity, the voter drops the envelope into the ballot box and signs his voter registration card.
 The French electoral code regulates operations quite strictly.
 Since 1988, the ballot boxes must be transparent so that voters and observers can see that no envelopes are present at the start of the vote and that no envelopes are added, except those of the duly counted and authorized voters.
 Candidates may send representatives to attend each stage of the process. In the evening, the votes are counted by volunteers under high supervision, according to specific procedures.
