 A study published Thursday in the journal Science detailed the genesis of a new species of bird in the Galápagos Islands.
 Researchers from Princeton University in the United States and Uppsala University in Sweden have indicated that the new species evolved in only two generations, although this process was estimated to be much longer, following reproduction between an endemic Darwin's finch, Geospiza fortis, and the immigrant conical-billed finch, Geospiza conirostris.
 Gold can be shaped in many ways. It can be rolled into tiny pieces
 It can be drawn into fine wire, which can be twisted and braided. It can be hammered or rolled into sheets.
 It can be made very thin, and glued to another metal. It can be so thin that it has sometimes been used to decorate hand-painted images in books called "illuminated manuscripts".
 This is called the pH of a chemical. You can make a pH indicator using red cabbage juice.
 The juice of the cabbage changes color depending on the acidity or basicity (alkalinity) of the chemical.
 The pH level is indicated by the amount of hydrogen ions (the H in pH) present in the chemical being tested.
 Hydrogen ions are protons that have been stripped of their electron (since hydrogen atoms are made up of a proton and an electron).
 Mix the two dry powders together, then, with clean and wet hands, press them into a ball.
 The moisture on your hands will react with the outer layers, which will cause a strange sensation and produce a kind of shell.
 The cities of Harappa and Mohenjo-daro had toilets equipped with a flushing system in almost every house, connected to a sophisticated sewage system.
 Remains of sewage systems have been found in the houses of the Minoan towns of Crete and Santorini in Greece.
 There were also toilets in ancient Egypt, Persia and China. In the Roman civilization, toilets were sometimes part of public baths where men and women mingled.
 When you call someone who is thousands of miles away, you use a satellite.
 The satellite receives the call in space and then sends it back to Earth, almost instantly.
 The satellite was sent into space by a rocket. Scientists use telescopes in space because the Earth's atmosphere distorts some of our light and vision.
 It takes a giant rocket more than 30 meters high to put a satellite or a telescope into space.
 The wheel changed the world in many ways. The greatest benefit it brought us was to make transportation much simpler and faster.
 This has brought us the train, the car and many other means of transport.
 Below are medium-sized felines that eat medium-sized prey, ranging from rabbits to antelope and other deer.
 In addition, there are many small cats (including free-ranging domestic cats) that eat many more small prey items, such as insects, rodents, lizards and birds.
 The secret of their success is the concept of niche, a special task assigned to each feline, preventing it from entering into competition with others.
 Lions are the most social of cats, living in large groups called prides.
 The packs are composed of one to three adult males related, as well as about thirty females and cubs.
 Women are generally very close to each other, as their family is composed of a large number of sisters and daughters.
 Lion prides act like wolf or dog packs, animals that are surprisingly similar to lions (but not other big cats) in their behavior, and also very deadly to their prey.
 A balanced athlete, the tiger can climb (but sometimes with difficulty), swim, jump long distances and pull with five times the force of a strong human.
 The tiger is part of the same family (genus Panthera) as lions, leopards and jaguars, and is the only cat that roars.
 The roar of the tiger does not resemble the full-throated roar of the lion, but rather a sentence whose words would be cries and growls.
 Ocelots are fond of small animals. They catch monkeys, snakes, rodents and birds if they can. Almost all the animals that an ocelot hunts are much smaller than it is.
 According to scientists, ocelots hunt and find food (prey) by smell, sniffing their path on the ground.
 They see very well in the dark thanks to their night vision, and they move very stealthily. Ocelots stalk their prey, blending into their environment before pouncing on them.
 When a small group of living things (a small population) is separated from the main population it came from (for example, if it moves over a mountain range or a river, or if it moves to a new island so that it cannot easily return), it often finds itself in a different environment from the one it was in before.
 This new environment has different resources and competitors, so the new population will need new features or adaptations to be a strong competitor compared to what it needed before.
 The original population has not changed at all, it still needs the same adaptations.
 Over time, as the new population adapts to its new environment, it begins to look less and less like the other population.
 After thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will look so different that they can no longer be considered the same species.
 We call this process “speciation,” which simply means the formation of new species. Speciation is an inevitable consequence and a very important part of evolution.
 Plants produce oxygen that humans breathe, and they absorb the carbon dioxide that humans exhale (i.e., breathe out).
 Plants produce their food using the sun through photosynthesis. They also provide shade.
 We make our houses and our clothes from plants. Most of the food we eat is plants. Without plants, animals would not survive.
 The mosasaur was the super-predator of the time, it feared nothing, except other mosasaurs.
 Its long jaws were lined with over 70 razor-sharp teeth, plus an extra set of teeth in the palate, so that anything that crossed its path could not escape.
 We're not sure, but it may have had a forked tongue. Its diet included turtles, large fish, other mosasaurs, and it may have been cannibalistic.
 He also attacked anything that came into the water; even a giant dinosaur like a T. rex was no match for him.
 Although the Romans ate foods we know today, they also ate some strange or unusual dishes, including wild boar, peacocks, snails, and the shrew, a type of rodent.
 Another difference: while the poor and the woman ate their food while sitting on chairs, the rich men liked to organize banquets together where they rested on the side while they ate.
 Ancient Roman meals could not include these foods of American or Asian origin, which were introduced to Europe centuries later.
 For example, they had no corn, tomatoes, potatoes, or cocoa, and no ancient Roman ever tasted turkey.
 The Babylonians built for each of their gods a main temple which was considered as the god's home.
 People made sacrifices to the gods and priests tried to meet the gods' needs through ceremonies and festivals.
 Each temple had an open courtyard, then an inner sanctuary that only priests could enter.
 Some pyramid towers, ziggurats, were sometimes built as elements of a temple.
 The top of the tower was a special sanctuary for the god.
 In the hot climate of the Middle East, the house was not so important.
 Most of the Jewish family's life took place outdoors.
 Women cooked in the courtyard; shops were only open counters on the street; houses were built of stone.
 As there were no large forests in the land of Canaan, wood was extremely expensive.
