 A civilization is a unique culture shared by a large group of people who live and work in cooperation, a society.
 The word "civilization" is derived from the Latin word "civilis", which means civil and is related to the Latin words "civis", which means citizen, and "civitas", which means large city or city-state and which also indicates, in some way, the size of the society to which it refers.
 City-states are the precursors of nations. A civilizational culture implies the transmission of knowledge over several generations, a lasting cultural imprint and a fair distribution.
 Minority cultures often disappear without leaving any relevant historical traces and are not recognized as true civilizations.
 During the Revolutionary War, the thirteen states first formed a weak central government—the Congress being its only component—under the Articles of Confederation.
 The Congress had no power to impose taxes, and, as there was no national executive or judicial authority, it relied on the state authorities, often uncooperative, to enforce all its acts.
 Nor did it have the power to derogate from tax laws or from customs duties between the states.
 The articles required unanimous consent of all states before they could be amended, and the states took the central government so lightly that their representatives were often absent.
