 Most of the buildings adjacent to the complex have been reconstructed to give tourists a better idea of what they looked like originally.
 In 1976, thirty percent of Machu Picchu had been restored and this restoration continues to this day.
 For example, the most common photographic format in the world is 35 mm; it was the most common film format at the end of the analogue era.
 It is still manufactured today, but what matters is that its image format is inherited from the format of the digital camera's photographic sensor.
 The 35mm format is actually, and this is quite confusing, 36mm wide by 24mm high.
 So the aspect ratio of this format (by dividing by twelve to get the simplest of whole number ratios) is 3:2.
 Many common formats (the APS family, for example) are equal to this aspect ratio or close to it.
 The third-party rule, which is often abused and ridiculed, is a simple directive that stimulates dynamism while offering protection to the image.
 It indicates that the most effective place for the main subject is at the intersection of the lines dividing the image into thirds vertically and horizontally (see example).
