 To understand the Templars, one must understand the context that led to the creation of the order.
 These events took place in the period generally considered as the High Middle Ages – the period of European history from the 11th to the 13th century (1000-1300).
 The Central Middle Ages was preceded by the High Middle Ages and followed by the Low Middle Ages, which conventionally ends around 1500.
 Technological determinism is a term that encompasses a wide range of ideas in practice, ranging from technological push or technological imperative to a strict sense in which the fate of humanity is dictated by an underlying logic related to scientific laws and their manifestation in technologies.
 Most interpretations of technological determinism agree on two general ideas: technological development itself proceeds according to a process that largely transcends cultural and political influences, and technology has an impact on intrinsically rather than socially conditioned societies.
 For example, one could say that the automobile necessarily leads to the development of roads.
 However, a national road network is not economically viable for a handful of cars, so new production methods are being developed to reduce the cost of owning a car.
 Massive car ownership also leads to a greater incidence of road accidents, which leads to the invention of new techniques in the field of healthcare to treat the resulting injuries.
 Romanticism presented an important element of cultural determinism, drawn from writers such as Goethe, Fichte and Schlegel.
 According to the theories of Romanticism, geography would have shaped individuals and, over time, customs and a culture related to this geography would have appeared, in harmony with the places occupied by society, preferable to laws imposed arbitrarily.
 In the same way that Paris is known as the capital of the world’s contemporary fashion, Constantinople was considered the capital of feudal Europe.
 Its reputation as a centre of luxury began around 400 AD and lasted until about 1100 AD.
 Its status declined in the twelfth century, mainly because the Crusaders returned laden with gifts such as silk and spices, with which the Byzantine markets could hardly compete.
 It was at this time that the title of fashion capital was transferred from Constantinople to Paris.
 The Gothic style reached its apogee between the 10th–11th century and the 14th century.
 At first, the dress was strongly influenced by the Byzantine culture in the east.
 However, due to the slowness of the means of communication, Western fashions could be delayed by 25 to 30 years.
 During the late Middle Ages, Western Europe began to develop its own style. One of the greatest advances of the time, following the Crusades, was the use of buttons for clothing fasteners.
 Subsistence agriculture is agriculture practiced to produce enough food to meet only the needs of the farmer and his or her family.
 Subsistence agriculture is a simple, often organic system using locally adapted seed stocks combined with crop rotation or other relatively simple techniques to maximize yield.
 Historically, most farmers practiced subsistence agriculture and this is still the case in many developing countries.
 Subcultures bring together individuals who feel neglected by societal norms and share the same ideas, which allows them to develop a sense of identity.
 Subcultures can be distinguished by age, ethnic origin, class, location and/or gender of members.
 The criteria that determine a subculture as distinct may be linguistic, aesthetic, religious, political, sexual, geographic, or a combination of factors.
 Members of a subculture often signal their membership by distinctive and symbolic use of style, which encompasses fashion, mannerisms, and slang.
 One of the most common methods used to illustrate the importance of socialization is to draw on the few unfortunate cases of children who, through neglect, misfortune or deliberate abuse, have not been socialized by adults during their childhood.
 These children are considered "feral" or wild. Some feral children have been confined by people (usually their own parents); in some cases, the abandonment of the child was due to the parents' rejection of a severe intellectual or physical disability of the child.
 Street children may have suffered serious abuse or trauma before being abandoned or running away.
 Others would have been raised by animals; some would have lived alone in the wild.
 When they are fully raised by non-human species, feral children display behaviors (within the limits of their physical dispositions) almost identical to those of the animals that raised them, such as fear or indifference towards humans.
 While project-based learning should make learning easier and more interesting, support goes further.
 Support is not a method of learning but rather a way to help learners who are discovering new learning such as using a new program or starting a new project.
 Supports can be both virtual and real. In other words, a teacher is a form of support, but the little man trombone of Microsoft Office is too.
 Virtual scaffolding is integrated into the software and is intended to question, guide and explain procedures that might have been too difficult to manage for the student alone.
 Children are placed in foster families for a variety of reasons ranging from neglect to abuse to extortion.
 No child should ever have to grow up in an environment that is not stimulating, nurturing and educational, but that is the case.
 We perceive the foster care system as a safe zone for these children.
 Our foster care system is supposed to provide safe homes, loving caregivers, stable education, and reliable health care.
 The foster care placement is supposed to provide all the necessities that were lacking in the home from which they were previously removed.
 The Internet combines elements of mass communication and interpersonal communication.
 The distinctive characteristics of the Internet lead to additional dimensions in terms of the approach to uses and gratifications.
 For example, "learning" and "socialization" are considered to be major factors in Internet use (James et al., 1995).
 “Personal involvement” and “continuous relationships” have also been identified as new motivational aspects by Eighmey and McCord (1998) when they studied public reactions to websites.
 The use of video recording has led to great discoveries in the interpretation of micro-expressions, that is, facial expressions lasting a few milliseconds.
 It is claimed that it is possible to detect whether a person is lying by correctly interpreting micro-expressions.
 Oliver Sacks, in his article The President’s Speech, indicated how people who cannot understand speech due to brain damage are nevertheless able to accurately assess sincerity.
 He even suggests that such capacities for interpreting human behavior may be found in animals such as domestic dogs.
 Research in the twentieth century has shown that there are two reservoirs of genetic variation: hidden and expressed.
 The mutation adds a new genetic variation, and selection removes it from the pool of expressed variations.
 Segregation and recombination alternate the variations between the two pools at each generation.
 In the savannah, it is difficult for a primate with a digestive system similar to that of humans to meet its amino acid needs from the available plant resources.
 In addition, a lack of reaction has serious consequences: growth disorders, malnutrition and ultimately death.
 The most easily accessible plant resources would be the proteins contained in leaves and legumes, but these are difficult to digest for primates like us, unless they are cooked.
 In contrast, food of animal origin (ants, termites, eggs) is easy to digest while providing a large amount of protein containing all the vital amino acids.
 All things considered, we should not be surprised if our own ancestors solved their "protein problem" in much the same way as savanna chimpanzees do today.
 Sleep interruption is the process of waking up intentionally during your sleep period and falling asleep again shortly after (10 to 60 minutes).
 This can be done easily by using a relatively quiet alarm clock, so that you can wake up without fully waking up.
 If you find yourself resetting the clock during your sleep, it can be placed on the other side of the room, forcing you to get out of bed to turn it off.
 Other biorythmic-based possibilities include drinking a lot of fluids before going to bed (especially water or tea, reputed to be diuretic), which forces you to wake up to urinate.
 The degree of inner peace of a person is opposed to the degree of tension in his body and mind.
 The lower the tension, the more positive the vital force is. Every person has the possibility to find absolute peace and contentment.
 Everyone can attain enlightenment. The only thing that stands in the way of this goal is our own tension and negativity.
 Tibetan Buddhism is based on the teachings of the Buddha, but has been enriched by the path of mahayana love and by many techniques of Indian yoga.
 In principle, Tibetan Buddhism is very simple: it consists of Kundalini Yoga, meditation and the path of universal love.
 With Kundalini Yoga, the Kundalini energy (energy of enlightenment) is awakened by yoga postures, breathing exercises, mantras and visualizations.
 The center of Tibetan meditation is the yoga of the deity. It is through the visualization of various deities that the energy channels are cleansed, the chakras activated, and the awakened consciousness created.
