 Two years after the end of the war, the former allies became enemies and the Cold War began.
 It would last for the next 40 years and see real fighting, through proxy armies, on battlefields in Africa and Asia, Afghanistan, Cuba and many other places.
 On September 17, 1939, the Polish defense was already broken, and the only hope was to retreat and reorganize along the Romanian bridgehead.
 But these plans became obsolete almost overnight, when more than 800,000 Soviet Red Army soldiers arrived and created the Belorussian and Ukrainian fronts after invading eastern Poland, violating the Riga Peace Treaty, the Soviet-Polish non-aggression pact, and other international treaties, whether bilateral or multilateral.
 The use of ships for the transport of goods is by far the most efficient way to move large amounts of people and goods across the oceans.
 The job of navies has traditionally been to ensure that your country retains the ability to move your people and your goods, while interfering with your enemy's ability to move their people and their goods.
 One of the most notable examples of this situation was the North Atlantic campaign during World War II. The Americans were trying to get soldiers and equipment across the Atlantic Ocean to help Britain.
 At the same time, the German Navy, using mainly U-Boats, tried to stop this traffic.
 Had the Allies failed, Germany would probably have been able to conquer Britain as it did the rest of Europe.
 It seems that goats were first domesticated about 10,000 years ago in the Zagros Mountains of Iran.
 Ancient cultures and tribes began to keep them close by for easy access to milk, hair, meat, and hides.
 Domestic goats were generally kept in herds that roamed the hills or other grazing areas, often tended by herdsmen who were usually children or adolescents, similar to the more familiar term shepherd. These pastoral methods are still in use today.
 The "wagonways" were built in England as early as the 16th century.
 Although the wagonways were simply made of parallel wooden planks, they allowed the horses that pulled them to reach greater speeds and to pull heavier loads than on the slightly more accident-prone roads of the day.
 The cross-ties were introduced early on to keep the tracks in place. However, it was soon realized that the tracks would be more effective if they were fitted with a strip of iron on top.
 This became a common practice, but the iron caused more wear on the wooden wheels of the wagons.
 Finally, wooden wheels were replaced by iron wheels. In 1767, the first iron rails appeared.
 The very first means of locomotion was walking: humans started walking upright two million years ago with the arrival of Homo Erectus (“upright man”).
 Their predecessors, the australopithecines, were not walking upright as usual.
 Bipedal specializations are found in Australopithecus fossils from 4.2 to 3.9 million years ago, although Sahelanthropus may have walked on two legs as early as seven million years ago.
 We can start by living in better harmony with the environment, we can join the environmental movement, and we can even campaign to mitigate future suffering.
 In many cases, it is a symptomatic treatment. However, if we do not want only a temporary solution, we must find the root of the problems and disable them.
 It is clear that the world has changed a lot due to the scientific and technological advances made by human beings, and that the problems have become more important due to the overpopulation and the extravagant lifestyle of humanity.
 After its adoption by Congress on July 4, a handwritten draft signed by Congress President John Hancock and Secretary Charles Thomson was then sent a few blocks away to the printing shop of John Dunlap.
 During the night, between 150 and 200 copies were made, today known as the "Dunlap Broadsides".
 The first public reading of the document was made by John Nixon in the Independence Hall courtyard on July 8.
 One of these was sent to George Washington on July 6, which he read to his troops in New York on July 9; a copy reached London on August 10.
 The 25 Dunlap broadsides that are known to exist are the earliest copies of the document; the original manuscript copy has not survived.
 Many paleontologists today think that a group of dinosaurs survived and are still alive. They are called birds.
 Few people consider them dinosaurs, given that they have wings and can fly.
 But there are many things about birds that still resemble dinosaurs.
 They have clawed feet covered in scales and have claws, they lay eggs and walk on their hind legs like T-Rex.
 Virtually all computers in use today are based on the manipulation of information that is coded in the form of binary numbers.
 A binary number can only have one of two values: 0 or 1. These numbers are called binary digits, or bits, in computer jargon.
 An internal poisoning may not be visible immediately. Symptoms, such as vomiting, are so general that an immediate diagnosis cannot be made.
 The best clue to an internal poisoning is probably the presence of an open container of toxic household chemicals or medications.
 Consult the label for specific first aid instructions for this poison.
 The term "insect" is used by entomologists in a formal sense for this group of insects.
 This term derives from an old familiarity with bedbugs, which are insects very adapted to parasitize humans.
 Bedbugs, like bedbugs, are nidicolous, that is, adapted to live in the nest or habitat of their host.
 In the United States, there are approximately 400,000 known cases of multiple sclerosis (MS), making it the leading neurological disease in young and middle-aged adults.
 Multiple sclerosis is a disease that affects the central nervous system, which includes the brain, spinal cord and optic nerve.
 Research has shown that women are twice as likely to have multiple sclerosis as men.
 A couple may very well feel that it is not in their interest, nor in the interest of the child, to take care of a baby.
 These couples can choose to make an adoption plan for their baby.
 In an adoption, the biological parents terminate their parental rights so that another couple can raise the child.
 The main goal of science is to understand how the world works through the scientific method. This method guides most scientific research.
 However, it is not the only one, experimentation, and an experiment is a test that serves to eliminate one or more of the possible hypotheses, ask questions and make observations, but also guides scientific research.
 Naturalists and philosophers focused on ancient texts, and in particular the Bible in Latin.
 The opinions of Aristotle on all scientific issues, including psychology, were accepted.
 With the decline of knowledge of Greek, the West was cut off from its Greek philosophical and scientific roots.
 Many rhythms observed in physiology and behavior often depend largely on the presence of endogenous cycles and their production by biological clocks.
 Periodic rhythms, which are not simply responses to periodic external stimuli, have been documented for most living things, including bacteria, fungi, plants, and animals.
 Biological clocks are self-sustaining oscillators that will continue a cycle of operation for a certain period of time, even in the absence of external stimulation.
 The Hershey and Chase experiment was one of the main indications that DNA was a genetic material.
 Hershey and Chase used phages, or viruses, to insert their own DNA into a bacterium.
 They conducted two experiments to label either the phage DNA with radioactive phosphorus or the phage protein with radioactive sulfur.
 Mutations can have many different effects depending on the type of mutation, the size of the part of the genetic material affected, and whether the affected cells are germ cells.
 Only mutations in germ cells can be passed on to children, while other mutations can cause cell death or cancer.
 Ecotourism is of interest to people who want to visit natural areas for the purpose of enjoying the landscape, including wildlife and flora.
 Hunting, fishing, photography, birdwatching, visiting parks and learning about the ecosystem are examples of activities on site.
 For example, you can go to see, photograph and discover the orangutans of Borneo.
 Every morning people leave the small country towns in their cars to go to work and they meet other people who are going to work in the countryside they have just left.
 In this dynamic transport shuttle, everyone is somehow connected to a system of transport based on private cars and supports it.
 Science now shows that this carbon-based economy has dislodged the biosphere from its state of stability that has supported human evolution for two million years.
 Everyone is part of society and uses transport systems. Virtually everyone complains about transport systems.
 In developed countries, it is rare to hear so many complaints about the quality of water or the collapse of bridges.
 Why do transportation systems generate so many complaints, why do they break down daily? Are transportation engineers simply incompetent, or is something more fundamental going on?
 Traffic flow is the study of the movements of drivers and individual vehicles between two points, and the interactions they have with each other.
 Unfortunately, it is difficult to study the flow of traffic because the behavior of drivers cannot be predicted with one hundred percent certainty.
 Fortunately, drivers tend to act within a reasonably consistent range; thus, traffic flows tend to have a reasonable consistency and can be approximated mathematically.
 To better represent the traffic flow, relationships were established between the three main characteristics: (1) the flow, (2) the density and (3) the speed.
 These relationships help in the planning, design, and operation of road facilities.
 Insects were the first animals to fly. Their ability to fly allowed them to escape their enemies more easily and to find food and mates more efficiently.
 Most insects have the advantage of being able to fold their wings along their bodies.
 This gives them a greater number of small places to hide from predators.
 Today, the only insects that cannot fold their wings are dragonflies and mayflies.
 A few thousand years ago, a man named Aristarchus claimed that the solar system was moving around the sun.
 Some thought he was right, but many believed the opposite: that the solar system was moving around the Earth, including the Sun (and even the other stars).
 This seems reasonable, because the Earth doesn't seem to be moving, does it?
 The Amazon River is the second longest and largest river on Earth. It carries more than eight times the volume of water of the second largest river.
 The Amazon is also the widest river in the world, sometimes reaching 10 km wide.
 No less than 20% of the water that flows from the planet's rivers into the oceans comes from the Amazon.
 The main arm of the Amazon River is 6,387 km (3,980 miles) long. It collects water from thousands of small rivers.
 Although stone pyramid building continued until the end of the Old Kingdom, the Giza pyramids were never surpassed in size and technical excellence of construction.
 Ancient Egyptians of the New Kingdom were awed by the monuments of their predecessors, which were then more than a thousand years old.
 The Vatican has about 800 inhabitants. It is the smallest independent country in the world, and the least populated.
 The Vatican City State drafts its legislation and official communications in Italian.
 Italian is also the everyday language used by most people who work in the state, while Latin is often used in religious ceremonies.
 The citizens of the Vatican City are all Catholic.
 Since ancient times, people have been familiar with basic chemical elements such as gold, silver and copper, as they occur in nature in their raw form and are quite simple to mine using primitive tools.
 Aristotle, a philosopher, theorized that everything is made up of a mixture of one or more of the four elements: earth, water, air, and fire.
 It was rather the four states of matter (in the same order) solid, liquid, gaseous and plasma, although he also put forward the theory that these transform into new substances to form what we see.
 Alloys are essentially a mixture of two or more metals. Remember that the periodic table contains many elements.
 Elements like calcium and potassium are considered metals. Of course, there are also metals like silver and gold.
 There are also alloys that include a small amount of non-metallic elements, such as carbon.
 Everything in the universe is made of matter. All matter is made of tiny particles called atoms.
 Atoms are so incredibly small that billions of them could fit into the period at the end of this sentence.
 So the pencil was a good friend to many people when it came out.
 Unfortunately, the advent of new writing methods has relegated the pen to a more private status and to rarer uses.
 People now write messages on computer screens, without ever having to approach a pencil sharpener.
 One can only wonder what the keyboard will become when the next novelty comes along.
 The fission bomb works on the principle of transforming energy by assembling a nucleus of a myriad of protons and neutrons.
 It's a bit like pushing a heavy cart up a hill. By splitting the core again, and then releasing some of that energy.
 Some atoms have an unstable nucleus, so they tend to break apart with little or no pressure.
 The surface of the moon is made up of rocks and dust. Its outer layer is called the crust.
 The thickness of the crust is about 70 km on the visible face and 100 km on the hidden face.
 It is thinner at sea level and thicker under the continents.
 There may be more maria on the near side because the crust is thinner and it was easier for the lava to rise to the surface.
 Content theories focus on what makes people feel good or what attracts them.
 These theories suggest that people have certain needs and/or desires that have been internalized as they mature into adulthood.
 These theories examine what motivates some people to want to do the things they do and what in their environment motivates them to do or not do certain things.
 Two popular content theories are Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs and Herzberg's Two-Factor Theory.
 In general, two behaviors can emerge when a manager becomes the boss of former colleagues: one is to try to remain the "good guy" (or "good gal").
 This type of manager has difficulty making unpopular decisions, taking disciplinary action, conducting evaluations, delegating responsibilities, and holding others accountable.
 At the other end of the spectrum, one transforms into an unrecognizable individual who feels that he/she must change everything the group has created so far and do things his/her own way.
 After all, the boss is ultimately responsible for the success and failure of the team.
 This behavior often leads to dissension between the leaders and the rest of the team.
 Virtual teams are subject to the same standards of excellence as conventional teams, but there are subtle differences.
 Members of a virtual team often function as the point of contact for their immediate physical group.
 They often have more autonomy than traditional team members because their teams can meet based on different time zones, which may not be understood by their local management.
 The presence of a real "invisible team" (Larson and LaFasto, 1989, p109) is also a unique element of a virtual team.
 The "invisible team" is the management team to which each member is accountable. It sets the standards for each of them.
 Why would an organization want to go through the tedious process of creating a learning structure? One of the goals of implementing organizational learning concepts is innovation.
 When all available resources are used effectively in the functional departments of an organization, creativity and ingenuity can flourish.
 Therefore, the process of an organization working together to overcome an obstacle can lead to a new innovative process to meet the customer’s need.
 Before an organization can be innovative, its management must create a culture of innovation, shared knowledge and its own culture of learning.
 Angel (2006) presents the Continuum Approach as a method used to help organizations achieve better results.
 Neurobiological data provides material evidence for a theoretical approach to the study of cognition, thus reducing the scope of research and making it much more precise.
 The correlation between brain pathology and behavior supports scientists in their research.
 It has long been known that different types of brain damage, injury, tumors and trauma affect behavior and cause changes in certain mental functions.
 The rise of new technologies allows us to see and study brain structures and processes never seen before.
 This gives us a lot of information and material to build simulation models that help us understand the processes in our mind.
 Although Artificial Intelligence is often strongly associated with science fiction, it represents a very important part of computer science that studies the behavior, learning and intelligent adaptation of a machine.
 Artificial intelligence research is aimed at the automation of intelligent behavior, i.e. actions that exhibit intelligence.
 Examples include control, planning and scheduling, the ability to respond to diagnostics and customer questions, and the recognition of handwriting, voice and face.
 These practices led to distinct disciplines, focused on providing solutions to the problems of everyday life.
 AI systems are now often used in the fields of economics, medicine, engineering, and the military, as well as in many home computer software and video games.
 Field trips are an integral part of any school class. Often, a teacher would like to take his or her students to places where a bus trip is not feasible.
 The solution is technology in the form of virtual field trips. Students can view ancient museum artifacts, visit an aquarium, or admire a beautiful work of art while sitting with their class.
 Participating in a virtual excursion is also a great way to think about a trip and share your experiences with future generations.
 For example, students at Bennet Elementary School in North Carolina design a website each year about their visit to the state capital. Each year, the site is updated, but the old versions are kept online to serve as an archive.
 Blogs can also help students improve their writing skills. Even if students often try the blogging experience with sloppy grammar and spelling, the fact of having an audience usually makes things better.
 As students are often the most critical audience, the blogger begins to strive to improve his writing to avoid criticism.
 In addition, blogging "forces students to become more aware of the world around them." The need to pique the interest of the public encourages students to be intelligent and interesting (Toto, 2004).
 Blogs are a tool that stimulates collaboration and encourages students to extend their learning well beyond the traditional school day.
 "When used well, blogs can help students to strengthen their analytical and critical thinking skills: by actively reacting to online content, they can compare their own views with those of others and express their own opinions on specific topics" (Oravec, 2002).
 Ottawa is the charming bilingual capital of Canada and has a large number of art galleries and museums that showcase Canada's past and present.
 Further south you will find the Niagara Falls and to the north, the Muskoka region and its surrounding areas which have a pristine natural beauty.
 All these measures, and many more, make Ontario what foreigners consider to be the quintessence of Canada.
 Large areas further north are sparsely populated and some are almost uninhabited in their wild state.
 For a population comparison that surprises more than one: There are more African-Americans living in the United States than Canadian citizens.
 The islands of East Africa are located in the Indian Ocean, off the east coast of Africa.
 Madagascar is by far the largest country, and even a continent in its own right, when it comes to wildlife.
 Most of the small islands are independent nations, or associated with France, and are known for being luxury beach resorts.
 The Arabs also brought the practice of Islam to the land and this religion spread widely to the Comoros and Mayotte.
 European influence and colonialism began in the 15th century, when the Portuguese explorer Vasco de Gama discovered the Cape route that connected Europe to India.
 To the north, the region is bounded by the Sahel, and to the south and west by the Atlantic Ocean.
