 The modern city of Casablanca was founded by Berber fishermen in the 10th century BC, and was used by the Phoenicians, Romans and Merinides as a strategic port called Anfa.
 The Portuguese, who had rebuilt it after destroying it and renamed it Casa Branca, finally abandoned it in 1755 after an earthquake.
 The Moroccan sultan rebuilt the city under the name of Daru l-Badya, and it was renamed Casablanca by Spanish merchants who established trading posts there.
 Casablanca is one of the least interesting places in all of Morocco for shopping.
 Around the old medina, you can easily find places to buy traditional Moroccan products, such as tagines, pottery, leather goods, hookahs and all sorts of trinkets, but that's it for tourists.
 Goma is a tourist city located in the extreme east of the Democratic Republic of the Congo, near Rwanda.
 In 2002, Goma was destroyed by the lava of the Nyiragongo volcano which buried most of the city’s streets, particularly the downtown area.
 Although Goma is reasonably safe, any visit outside of Goma should be researched to understand the state of fighting that continues in the province of North Kivu.
 The city is also the starting point for the ascent of the Nyiragongo volcano as well as for treks of mountain gorilla tracking among the cheapest in Africa.
 You can use boda-boda (motorcycle taxi) to move around Goma. The normal (local) price is about 500 Congolese francs for a short ride.
 Combined with its relative inaccessibility, "Timbuktu" has become a metaphor for remote and exotic lands.
 Today, Timbuktu is a poor city, although its reputation makes it a tourist attraction, and it has an airport.
 In 1990, it was added to the list of World Heritage in Danger, due to the threat of desert sands.
 It was one of the main stops on Henry Louis Gates's PBS series "Wonders of the African World."
 The city contrasts sharply with the rest of the country, as it has a more Arabic than African style.
 The Kruger National Park (KNP) is located in the northeast of South Africa and runs along the Mozambique border to the east, the Zimbabwe border to the north and the Crocodile River forms the southern border.
 The total area of the park is 19,500 km², which is divided into 14 ecozones, each with its own specific fauna.
 It is one of the most famous theme parks in South Africa and is considered the flagship of South African National Parks (SANParks).
 As with all South African national parks, there are daily conservation and entrance fees for the park.
 It may be advantageous to purchase a Wild Card which gives access to certain South African parks, as well as all South African national parks.
 The island of Hong Kong gives its name to the territory of Hong Kong and represents the main center of interest for many tourists.
 The row of buildings that draws the skyline of Hong Kong has been compared to a flashing bar graph, which is reflected in the waters of Victoria Harbour.
 To see the best views of Hong Kong, leave the island and head to the waterfront of Kowloon across the harbour.
 The vast majority of Hong Kong Island’s urban development is concentrated on the north shore landfills.
 It is the place that the British settlers invested in, so it seems to be a good starting point if you are looking for evidence of the colonial past of this region.
 The Sundarbans are the largest coastal mangrove belt in the world, stretching 80 km (50 miles) from the coast into the Bangladeshi and Indian hinterland.
 The Sundarbans have been declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The part of the forest located in Indian territory is called Sundarbans National Park.
 The forests are not, however, composed solely of mangrove swamps: they also contain some of the last remnants of the majestic jungles that once covered the Gangetic plain.
 The Sundarbans cover an area of 3,850 km², of which about one third is covered by water/marshes.
 Sundarbans is a nature reserve since 1966, you can find there about 400 royal Bengal tigers and 30,000 spotted deer.
 Buses leave from the interdistrict bus station (located on the other side) throughout the day, but most, particularly those serving the east and Jakar/Bumthang, leave between 6:30 and 7:30 a.m.
 Inter-district buses are often full, so it is advisable to buy a ticket a few days in advance.
 Most districts are served by small Japanese ferries, which are comfortable and sturdy.
 Shared taxis are a quick and comfortable way to get to nearby places such as Paro (150 Nu) and Punakha (200 Nu).
 The Oyapock Bridge is a cable-stayed bridge that spans the Oyapock River to link the cities of Oiapoque in Brazil and Saint-Georges-de-l'Oyapock in French Guiana.
 The two towers are 83 meters high; it is 378 meters long and has two lanes of 3.50 meters wide.
 The vertical clearance under the bridge is 15 meters. The structure was completed in August 2011, but it was not opened to traffic until March 2017.
 The bridge is expected to be fully operational in September 2017, when Brazilian customs control posts are expected to be completed.
 The Guaraní were the largest indigenous group in what is now eastern Paraguay, living as semi-nomadic hunter-gatherers and also practicing subsistence agriculture.
 Other indigenous tribes that inhabited the Chaco, such as the Guaycurú or the Payaguá, survived mainly thanks to fishing, hunting, or gathering.
 In the 16th century, Paraguay, once called the "giant province of the Indies", was born from the encounter between Spanish conquerors and indigenous populations.
 The Spanish inaugurated the period of colonization, which lasted three centuries.
 Since the founding of Asunción in 1537, Paraguay has managed to preserve much of its indigenous character and identity.
 Argentina is known for having one of the best teams and some of the best players in the world.
 The biggest tournament of the year takes place in December on the polo fields of Las Cañitas.
 In addition, smaller tournaments and matches are sometimes organized here at other times of the year.
 For information on tournaments and places to buy tickets for polo matches, see the Asociacion Argentina de Polo.
 The official currency of the Falkland Islands is the Falkland Islands Pound (FKP) which is equivalent to one British Pound (GBP).
 Money can be exchanged at the only bank on the islands, located in Stanley, across from the FIC West store.
 The pound sterling is a commonly accepted currency throughout the islands, while in Stanley, credit cards and US dollars are also often accepted.
 On the neighbouring islands, credit cards may not be accepted, even though British and American currencies may be. Talk to the owners in advance to agree on a method of payment.
 It is almost impossible to exchange money from the Falkland Islands outside the islands, so change it before leaving.
 Since Montevideo is located south of the Equator, winter in the northern hemisphere corresponds to summer there, and vice versa.
 Montevideo is located in a subtropical zone and summer temperatures exceeding 30 °C are common.
 Winter can be deceptively cold: temperatures rarely drop below freezing, but the wind and humidity combine to make it feel colder than the thermometer says.
 There are no real "rainy" and "dry" seasons: the rainfall is more or less constant throughout the year.
 Although many of the park's animals are used to seeing humans, they are still wild animals; please do not feed or disturb them.
 According to the park authorities, you must stay at least 100 meters away from bears and wolves and 25 meters away from all other wild animals!
 As docile as they may seem, the bison, elk, moose, bear and almost all large animals can attack.
 Every year, dozens of visitors are injured because they didn’t keep a safe distance. These animals are large, wild and potentially dangerous, so give them space.
 Also, be aware that odors attract bears and other wild animals, so avoid carrying or cooking smelly foods and keep the camp clean.
