 Anyone driving to high latitudes or crossing mountain passes should consider the possibility of snow, ice or freezing temperatures.
 On icy and snowy roads, the friction is low and you can't drive as if you were on bare asphalt.
 During blizzards, it can snow enough in a short time to block you in.
 Visibility may also be limited by snowfall or blowing snow, or by condensation or ice on vehicle windows.
 On the other hand, the presence of ice and snow is normal in many countries, and traffic is virtually uninterrupted all year round.
 Safaris are perhaps the greatest tourist attraction in Africa and the most memorable time for many visitors.
 In common parlance, the term "safari" refers to an excursion on the African land, and in particular in the savannah, with the aim of witnessing the spectacular sight of wild animals in their natural habitat.
 Some animals, such as elephants and giraffes, tend to come close to cars and standard equipment allows them to be well observed.
 Lions, cheetahs and leopards are sometimes shy and you will see them better with binoculars.
 A walking safari (also called a bushwalk, foot safari or footing) is a hike, either for a few hours or several days.
