 Fruit pies are common: apples are baked and cooked into pies all year round, while cherries and plums make an appearance in the summer.
 Many German bakery products also contain almonds, hazelnuts and other nuts. Popular cakes often go particularly well with a cup of strong coffee.
 If you want small but hearty pastries, try the Berliners, also called Berliner, Pfannkuchen or Krapfen depending on the region.
 A curry is a dish made with herbs and spices, accompanied by meat or vegetables.
 A curry dish can be either "solid" or "liquid", depending on the amount of sauce it contains.
 In the interior regions of northern India and Pakistan, yogurt is commonly used in curries; in southern India and some other coastal regions of the subcontinent, coconut milk is commonly used.
 With 17,000 islands, Indonesian cuisine is a generic term that covers a wide variety of regional cuisines found throughout the country.
 However, when this term is used without further qualification, it tends to refer to food from the central and eastern parts of the main island of Java.
 Now widely available throughout the archipelago, Javanese cuisine offers a range of simply seasoned dishes, the predominant flavours favoured by Javanese being peanuts, chillies, sugar (particularly Javanese coconut sugar) and various aromatic spices.
 The stirrups are supports for the rider's feet, which hang from either side of the saddle.
 They offer greater stability to the user, but they can pose a security problem: the user's feet can get stuck in them.
 If a rider is thrown from a horse but has a foot caught in the stirrup, he could be dragged if the horse runs away. To minimize this risk, a number of safety measures can be taken.
 First, most riders wear riding boots with a heel and a smooth, fairly narrow sole.
 Then some saddles, especially English ones, have safety bars that allow a stirrup to fall off the saddle if it is pulled back by a rider who falls.
 Cochamó Valley – The premier destination for rock climbing in Chile, known as the Yosemite of South America, with many great granite walls and cliffs.
 From the tops of the mountains, the views of the mountains are breathtaking. Mountaineers from all over the world are constantly discovering new routes on the slopes, where the possibilities are endless.
 Winter downhill sports, including skiing and snowboarding, are popular sports that involve sliding down a snow-covered slope with skis or a snowboard attached to the feet.
 Skiing is a major travel activity that has many aficionados, sometimes called "ski bums", who organize their entire vacations around skiing in specific locations.
 The idea of skiing is very old: some cave paintings showing skiers date back to 5,000 BC!
 The practice of alpine skiing as a sport dates back at least to the 17th century; the first ski club was founded in 1861 in Australia by Norwegians.
 Cross-country skiing: this activity is also called Nordic skiing, cross-country skiing or ski touring.
 It resembles alpine touring skiing, as well as mountaineering, without generally incorporating these activities, which are practiced on rough terrain and require the use of much stiffer skis and boots.
 Think of the ski route as a similar hiking route.
 In good conditions, you can cover a little more distance than on foot – but you will rarely reach the speeds of cross-country skiing without a heavy backpack on groomed trails.
 Europe is a relatively small continent, but it has many independent countries, so traveling through several countries usually means applying for several visas and having several passports checked.
 The Schengen area, however, works a bit like a single country in this regard.
 As long as you stay in this zone, you can generally cross borders without going through passport control again.
 Likewise, by having a Schengen visa, you do not need to apply separately for a visa for each of the member countries of the area, which saves time, money and administrative formalities.
 There is no universal definition of what constitutes an antique. Some tax authorities define antiques as items over 100 years old.
 The criteria vary depending on where you are; in some parts of the world, such as North America, the age limit may be lower than in Europe.
 Handmade products may be considered antiques, even if they are less old than similar industrial products.
 Reindeer herding is an important means of livelihood for the Sami people and the culture surrounding this trade is of great importance to many other professions.
 Although, according to tradition, not all Sámi were involved in large-scale reindeer herding, they lived off fishing, hunting and other similar activities, using reindeer mainly as draft animals.
 Today, many Sámi people work in modern professions. Tourism is an important source of income in the Sámi region of Lapland.
 Although widely used, especially among non-Roma, the term “Gypsy” is often considered pejorative due to its association with negative stereotypes and a misrepresentation of the Roma people.
 If the country you are travelling to is subject to a travel advisory issued by your government, your travel insurance or your travel cancellation insurance may be affected.
 You can also seek advice from other governments, but their advice is tailored to their citizens.
 As an example, American citizens in the Middle East may face different situations than Europeans or Arabs.
 Opinions are only a brief summary of a country's political situation.
 The opinions presented are often superficial, general and too simplified compared to the more detailed information available elsewhere.
 Severe weather is the generic term for any dangerous weather phenomenon that can cause damage, serious social disruption, or loss of life.
 Very unfavorable weather conditions can occur anywhere in the world, and they can be of several kinds, depending on geographical, topographical and atmospheric features.
 Severe winds, hail, excessive rainfall, and wildfires are forms and effects of severe weather, as are thunderstorms, tornadoes, waterspouts, and hurricanes.
 Extreme weather phenomena, regional and seasonal, include cold snaps, snowstorms with high winds, and sand or dust storms.
 It is strongly recommended that travellers research the risks of bad weather that may affect their destination area, as this may affect the itineraries they are considering.
 Anyone who is considering going to a country that could be considered a war zone should receive professional training.
 A search on the internet for "Courses in hostile environment" will probably provide the address of a local company.
 A course will normally cover all the issues discussed here in much more detail, usually with practical experience.
 A course normally lasts from 2 to 5 days and includes role-playing games, a lot of first aid, and sometimes weapons training.
 Books and magazines about survival in the wilderness are common, but publications about war zones are few.
 Travellers who plan to have gender reassignment surgery abroad should ensure they have valid documents for their return journey.
 The willingness of governments to issue passports with no gender designation (X) or to update documents to match the name and gender a person prefers varies.
 The willingness of foreign governments to honor these documents is equally variable.
 Security checkpoint searches have also become much more intrusive in the post-September 11, 2001 era.
 Transgender people in the preoperative phase should not expect to pass scanners while preserving their privacy and dignity.
 Rip currents are currents that return from the waves that break on the beach, often on a reef or equivalent.
 Due to the underwater topography, the return flow is concentrated in a few deeper sections, and a fast current towards the deep water can form there.
 In most cases, deaths are due to exhaustion resulting from an attempt to swim against the current, which can be impossible.
 As soon as you get out of the current, the return to swimming is not more difficult than usual.
 Try to aim for a place where you won't be caught again. It is also possible, depending on your skill and whether or not you have been spotted, that you may want to wait for help.
 The re-entry shock occurs earlier than the culture shock (the honeymoon phase is shorter), lasts longer and can be more severe.
 Travelers who have had a hard time adjusting to the new culture sometimes have a hard time adjusting to their home culture.
 When you return home after living abroad, you have already adapted to the new culture and have lost some of your original culture's habits.
 At first, when you went abroad, people were probably patient and understanding, knowing that travelers in a new country have to adjust.
 People may not anticipate that patience and understanding are also needed for travellers returning home.
 The sound and light show at the pyramid is one of the most interesting attractions in the area for children.
 You can see the pyramids in the dark and you can see them in silence before the show begins.
 Usually, you can always hear the noise of tourists and vendors. The history of sound and light is like a history book.
 The Sphinx is placed as the backdrop and narrator of a long story.
 The scenes are displayed on the pyramids and the different pyramids are lit up.
 The South Shetland Islands, discovered in 1819, are claimed by several nations and have the largest number of research stations and sixteen of them are active in 2020.
 The archipelago is located 120 km north of the mainland and the largest island, King George Island, is home to the village of Villa Las Estrellas.
 Other examples are Livingston and Deception Island, where the flooded caldera of an active volcano provides a spectacular natural harbor.
 Ellsworth Land is the southern region of the peninsula, bounded by the Bellingshausen Sea.
 The mountains of the peninsula merge into the plateau, then reappear to form the Ellsworth mountain range, 360 km long and crossed by the Minnesota glacier.
 The northern part, or Sentinel Range, contains the highest mountains in Antarctica, the Vinson Massif, which rises to 4,892 m (16,050 ft).
 In remote areas without cell phone coverage, you may have no choice but to use satellite phone service.
 A satellite phone usually does not replace a cell phone, because you have to be outside and have a clear view of the satellite to make a call.
 It is a service often used by shipping, including pleasure craft, as well as expeditions that have remote data transmission and telephony needs.
 Your local phone company should be able to tell you more about connecting to this service.
 Those who plan a gap year have the opportunity to learn while traveling, and more and more of them are choosing this option.
 This formula is particularly appreciated by young people who leave school, as it allows them to take a year off before university, without compromising their studies.
 Often, having taken a gap year abroad can actually give you a better chance of getting into higher education in your home country.
 In general, there is a fee to take these educational programs.
 Finland is a popular destination for boating. The “Land of a thousand lakes” also has thousands of islands, both in the lakes and in the coastal archipelagos.
 You don't necessarily need a yacht in the archipelago and on the lakes.
 While the coastal archipelagos and the larger lakes are indeed large enough for a yacht, smaller boats or even kayaks offer a different experience.
 Boating is a national pastime in Finland, with one boat for every seven or eight people.
 Norway, Sweden and New Zealand are in the same situation, but apart from that, it is a unique case (in the Netherlands, for example, the figure is one to forty).
 Most Baltic cruises feature an extended stay in St. Petersburg, Russia.
 This means you can visit the historic city for a few full days while returning to the boat at night.
 If you only go to land with cruise excursions, you will not need a separate visa (as of 2009).
 The city of Berlin, Germany, is mentioned in some brochures for cruises. As you can see from the map above, Berlin is not at all near the sea and no visit to this city is included in the price of the cruise.
 Flying can be a scary experience for people of all ages and backgrounds, especially if they have never flown before or have experienced a traumatic event.
 There is no shame in this: it is no different from the fears and anxieties that many people have about other things.
 For some, understanding something about how planes work and what happens during a flight can help to overcome a fear that is based on the unknown or on not having control.
 Transport companies are well paid to make fast deliveries. Often, in the context of an urgent repair, the question of deadlines is crucial for the documents, goods or spare parts involved.
 On some routes, large companies have their own planes, but on other routes and for small companies, there has been a problem.
 If they had sent the goods by air freight, on some routes it would have taken days to get through the unloading and customs.
 The only way to get it there faster was to send it as checked baggage. Airline regulations will not allow them to send a bag without a passenger, and that's where you come in.
 The most obvious way to travel first class or business class is to shell out a lot of money for that privilege (or, better yet, have your company do it for you).
 However, it is not cheap: you can expect to pay up to four times the normal economy fare for business class, and eleven times for first class!
 In general, it is pointless to try to get discounts for business class or first class seats on direct flights from A to B.
 Airlines know very well that they can count on a certain type of traveller who is willing to pay a high price for the privilege of speed and comfort, and they set their fares accordingly.
 The capital of Moldova is Chisinau. The local language is Romanian, but Russian is widely spoken.
 Moldova is a multi-ethnic republic that suffers from ethnic conflicts.
 In 1994, this conflict led to the creation of the self-proclaimed Transnistria Republic in eastern Moldova, with its own government and currency, but not recognized by any UN member state.
 Economic ties have been re-established between these two parts of Moldova despite the failure of political negotiations.
 The main religion in Moldova is Orthodox Christianity.
 With a population of 3.7 million, Izmir is Turkey's third largest city, the second largest port after Istanbul, and an excellent hub.
 What was once the ancient city of Smyrna is now a modern, developed and vibrant commercial centre, set around a huge bay, surrounded by mountains.
 The wide boulevards, glass-fronted buildings and modern shopping centres are dotted with traditional red-tiled roofs, the 18th-century market, and old mosques and churches, although the city has an atmosphere more reminiscent of Mediterranean Europe than traditional Turkey.
 The village of Haldarsvík offers views of the neighbouring island of Eysturoy and is home to an unusual octagonal church.
 In the cemetery, there are interesting marble sculptures representing doves on some tombs.
 It is worth walking for half an hour in this fascinating village.
 The romantic and fascinating town of Sintra, located to the north, is easily accessible and was made famous to foreigners by the glowing account of its splendor that was written by Lord Byron.
 The bus 403 of Scotturb goes regularly to Sintra, with a stop at Cabo da Roca.
 On your way north, be sure to visit the beautiful sanctuary of Our Lady of Fatima (temple), a place worldwide known for the apparitions of Mary.
 Remember that you are visiting essentially a cemetery, as well as a site that has an almost incalculable significance for a large part of the world's population.
 There are still many women and men alive who survived their stay here, and many others who saw their relatives murdered or killed by forced labour, Jews and non-Jews alike.
 Please treat the site with all the dignity, solemnity and respect it deserves. Do not make jokes about the Holocaust or Nazis.
 Do not deface the site by marking or scratching graffiti on the structures.
 The official languages of Barcelona are Catalan and Spanish. About half of the inhabitants prefer to speak Catalan, a large majority understand it, and virtually everyone is able to speak Spanish.
 However, most of the signs are only in Catalan, as the law states that it is the first official language.
 However, Spanish is also widely used in public transport and other facilities.
 Regular announcements in the metro are made only in Catalan, but unscheduled disruptions are announced by an automated system in many languages, including Spanish, English, French, Arabic and Japanese.
 Parisians have a reputation for being self-centered, rude and arrogant.
 Although this stereotype is often inaccurate, the best way to get along in Paris is to behave as well as possible, to act like a good person. This will make your travels considerably easier.
 The abrupt outsides of Parisians evaporate quickly if you show a minimum of courtesy.
