 Pre-modern observatories are generally obsolete today, and remain in place as museums or education sites.
 As light pollution at their time was not as preoccupying as today, they are generally located in cities or on campuses, more easily accessible than those built in the modern era.
 Most modern research telescopes are huge infrastructures placed in remote regions where the atmospheric conditions are favorable.
 The contemplation of cherry blossoms, known as hanami, has been a part of Japanese culture since the 8th century.
 The concept came from China where plum blossoms were the flower of choice.
 In Japan, the first cherry blossom festivals were organized by the emperor for himself and other members of the aristocracy around the imperial court.
 Plants look their best when they are in their natural environment, so resist the temptation to take just "one" home.
 If you visit a strictly landscaped garden, the collection of "specimens" will also get you kicked out without discussion.
