 Christmas is one of the most important holidays in Christianity, it celebrates the birth of Jesus.
 Many traditions associated with these holidays have also been adopted by non-believers in Christian countries and by non-Christians worldwide.
 It is a tradition to spend the night of Easter awake in an open place to see the sunrise.
 There are of course Christian theological explanations for this tradition, but it may well be a pre-Christian spring and fertility ritual.
 More traditional churches often hold an Easter Vigil on Saturday night during the Easter weekend, with congregations often bursting into the party at midnight to celebrate the resurrection of Christ.
 All the animals that have arrived on these islands have done so originally by water, either swimming or on floating objects, or by air.
 Due to the great distance that separates them from the mainland, mammals were unable to make the journey, making the giant tortoise the main grazing animal of the Galapagos.
 Since humans arrived in the Galapagos, many mammals have been introduced, including goats, horses, cows, rats, cats and dogs.
 If you visit the Arctic or Antarctic regions in winter, you may experience polar night, during which the sun does not rise above the horizon.
 This is a good opportunity to see the Northern Lights, as the sky will be dark for most of the day.
 As the regions are sparsely populated, and light pollution is therefore often not a problem, you can also enjoy the stars.
 The Japanese work culture is more hierarchical and formal than what Westerners may be used to.
 The costumes are classic workwear, and employees are addressed by their last name or by their job title.
 Harmony in the workplace is crucial, as it emphasizes the collective effort rather than praising individual achievements.
 Workers often need to get approval from their superiors for any decisions they make and are expected to follow their superiors' instructions without question.
